\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix a prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We want to discuss some aspects of the theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-rings.
 This theory provides a good language to talk about rings with a lift of
 Frobenius modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
note
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(a^{p})=\delta(a)a^{(p-1)p}+(a+p\delta(a))\delta(a^{p-1})=\delta(a)a^{(p-1)p}+(a+p\delta(a))(\delta(a)a^{(p-2)p}+(a+p\delta(a))\delta(a^{p-2})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(a^{p})=2\delta(a)a^{(p-1)p}+p\delta(a)^{2}a^{(p-2)p}+(a+p\delta(a))^{2}\delta(a^{p-2})+\delta(a^{p-2})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(a^{2})=2\delta(a)(a^{2}+\delta(a))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Definition and Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset


\series bold
-ring 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\delta)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\colon A\to A$
\end_inset

 is a map of sets with 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(0)=\delta(1)=0$
\end_inset

 satisfying the following two identities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2}\in A$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(a_{1}a_{2})=\delta(a_{1})a_{2}^{p}+a_{1}^{p}\delta(a_{2})+p\delta(a_{1})\delta(a_{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2}\in A$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(a_{1}+a_{})=\delta(a)+\delta(b)+\frac{a^{p}+b^{p}-(a+b)^{p}}{p}=\delta(a)+\delta(b)-\sum_{i=1}^{p-1}\frac{1}{p}{p \choose i}a^{i}b^{p-i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is an evident category of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-rings.
 If the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-stucture on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is clear from context, we often supress it from the notation and simply
 call 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring equipped with a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon A\to A$
\end_inset

 that lifts the Frobenius on 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash p$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, we have an equation of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(a)=a^{p}+p\delta(a),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\colon A\to A$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we claim that equipping 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 gives it the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-ring.
 Indeed, we clearly have 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(0)=\delta(1)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Also, since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a^{p}b^{p}+p\delta(ab) & =\phi(ab)\\
 & =\phi(a)\phi(b)\\
 & =(a^{p}+p\delta(a))(b^{p}+p\delta(b))\\
 & =a^{p}b^{p}+p(a^{p}\delta(b)+b^{p}\delta(a)+p\delta(a)\delta(b)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(ab)=a^{p}\delta(b)+b^{p}\delta(a)+p\delta(a)\delta(b)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\delta(a+b) & =\frac{\phi(a+b)-(a+b)^{p}}{p}\\
 & =\frac{\phi(a)+\phi(b)-(a+b)^{p}}{p}\\
 & =\frac{a^{p}+b^{p}+p(\delta(a)+\delta(b))-(a+b)^{p}}{p}\\
 & =\delta(a)+\delta(b)+\frac{a^{p}+b^{p}-(a+b)^{p}}{p}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We can also go backwards:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\colon A\to A$
\end_inset

 provides a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon A\to A$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(a)=a^{p}+p\delta(a)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, is an endomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which lifts the Frobenius on 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-torsionfree, the construction (1) gives a bijective correspondence between
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-structures on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and Frobenius lifts on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-torsionfree, it is better to record 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

